Journal of Environmental Management

Research article
Variability of chlorophyll and the influence factors during winter in seasonally ice-covered lakes

Author links open overlay panel, Kaishan Song a b, , , , , , , , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jenvman.2020.111338Get rights and content
Full text access

Highlights

  • •
    Nutrients concentrations in frozen period were comparable with ice-free period.
  • •
    Chla in ice-covered season was correlated with the value in the previous autumn.
  • •
    Chla in winter was mainly related to TNwater TPcd in ice-covered lakes.
  • •
    TNwater, TPcd, and TSM could explain 77.8% of Chla variances in winter.

Abstract

Lake ice is an essential and integral part of the cryosphere and freshwater systems. The formation of lake ice affects the physical, hydrological, and biological conditions of ecological systems. Global warming may contribute to even shorter periods of ice cover in the lakes of the Frigid Zone, which adversely affects the growth of phytoplankton and primary productivity. This study was conducted for the purpose of evaluating the growth of phytoplankton and factors involved, in 28 ice-covered lakes across the Songnen Plain, in the Northeast of China, to understand how they take part in the whole-ecosystem functioning. A total of 1026 water samples were collected in April, September, and January during the period 2014–2018. In the frozen period, the concentration levels of dissolved organic carbon (DOC), total nitrogen (TN), and total phosphorus (TP) were all comparable with the spring and autumn. Despite the limited light availability and low temperature, the phytoplankton survived in sub-ice waters during winter with a low concentration of chlorophyll a (Chla). Its average concentration was positively correlated with the concentration observed in the previous autumn (rp = 0.563, p < 0.01). According to the regression tree analysis, during the winter period, Chla was mainly related to the concentration of TN in sub-ice water (TNwater) and with the difference of concentration of TP between water and ice (TPcd). Furthermore, either in ice or in sub-ice water, the concentration of Chla was also significantly affected by total suspended matter (TSM) (p < 0.05). The levels of TNwater, TPcd, and TSM could explain the 77.8% of the variance in the concentration of Chla during winter with contributions in the ranges of 25.5%–35.0%, 9.2%–11.3%, and 21.5%–34.0%, respectively (p < 0.05). This research substantially contributes to comprehending how the existing conditions under-ice affect the whole ecosystem when the ice cover is reduced lakes or rivers.

1. Introduction

Lakes located above 45° North are ice-covered during winter, where climate changes and associated feedbacks are having profound impacts on northern environments (Callaghan et al., 2010). The melting of glaciers has reduced ice cover on lakes and rivers worldwide, and this has led the need for urgent research activities, particularly for ecosystem under-ice (Hampton et al., 2017; Yang et al., 2019). The ecology dynamic in ice-covered lakes should be further explored for understanding the contributions to the whole ecosystem processes, the regulation of the flux of nutrients among compartments, and for predicting the future greenhouse gas emissions to the cryosphere and boreal lakes. It has been proved that CO2 is always accumulated below the ice and largely emitted when the ice melts. CH4 is also prone to be oxidized into CO2 at the water-ice interface and in the sub-ice water column (Kankaala et al., 2006; Martinez-Cruz et al., 2015; Wand et al., 2006). Even though winter is not favorable, it has been shown that there is a biological activity in sub-ice water (Deng et al., 2020; Kalinowska et al., 2019; Palshin et al., 2019) and that the importance of primary production in ice-covered lakes during winter is increasingly recognized in lake metabolism (Katz et al., 2015). This underlines the role of winter ecology in the study of changes in environmental conditions of lakes and their biogeochemical cycles.
Water temperature is also critical for the lake ecology (Maberly et al., 2020). In winter, both the temperature and the duration of the cover of snow or ice are the main abiotic drivers of biological processes (Katz et al., 2015). Evidence shows that winter conditions play an essential role in the seasonality of phytoplankton communities in lakes with ice cover and that taxa under-ice can serve as residual inocula for the growth of phytoplankton during spring (Gerten and Adrian, 2000; Kalinowska et al., 2019; Yang et al., 2016). In fact, there had been various events of phytoplankton bloom below the ice during winter in many lakes, such as Lake Baikal, Lake Erie, Lake Erken, and lakes in central Japan (Maeda and Ichimura, 1973; Twiss et al., 2014; Yang et al., 2016). However, the factors underlying the growth of phytoplankton in sub-ice water remain to be determined. Several aspects of the events that happen when ice covers lakes or when has melted, known as ice-in and ice-out, respectively, are not fully known mainly due to the difficulty of access and the need of special vehicles (Kiili et al., 2009; Song et al., 2019). In previous studies, it has been shown that certain characteristics of the snow and ice, such as cleanliness, snow coverage, and ice thickness, all could affect algal blooms during winter given by the transmission rate of the photosynthetically active radiation (Bolsenga and Vanderploeg, 1992; Katz et al., 2015). The concentration of nutrients is also a factor that affects the growth of phytoplankton in sub-ice water during winter (Hampton et al., 2017; Jiang et al., 2019).
On the other hand, lake conditions depend upon external and internal factors that affected the ecosystem in previous seasons. The duration of ice cover and the timing of ice-on and ice-off varies from one to another lake (Yang et al., 2019). Among different lakes, the community composition and biomass are highly variable spite of phytoplankton generally appear under the ice. With this in view, a greater understanding of the role of nutrients, the concentration of dissolved organic carbon (DOC) under the ice during winter, and the adjacent seasons will help to identify the driving factors in the phytoplankton dynamics in ice-covered lakes. In the water, the total suspended matter (TSM) can absorb and scatter the sunlight, thus influencing the photosynthetic process and total primary production (Wozniak et al., 2018). Meanwhile, the pigment part in TSM mainly derived from the plankton. Studies have been proven that TSM content could increase with Chla in aquatic ecosystems (Marcel et al., 2003; Ylostalo et al., 2014).
Northeast China has the lakes with a total area of 4700 km2, a part is in the cold temperate region, with a monsoon climate (Ma et al., 2011). The annual average temperature is about 3-6 °C, and the lakes in this region are generally covered with ice for more than 4 months each year, typically from November to March (Song et al., 2019). To study the effect of ice formation on phytoplankton, water samples collected, on a seasonal basis, from lakes or reservoirs in Northeast China. The different conditions existing between lakes were evaluated during winter (ice-on) and spring and autumn (ice-off) concerning the changes in the level of nutrients, DOC, and chlorophyll a (Chla). The species of phytoplankton that survive during the ice-snow covered season are significantly less than ice-off periods due to a low-light environment, which is unfavorable. Both the direction of change of Chla from ice-on to ice-off conditions and the variables affecting such changes are crucial to the location of lakes seasonally ice-covered in the ecological cycle. The objective of this study was to monitor the concentration of Chla and quantify the main factors affecting the level of Chla under the ice in the lakes in Northeast China. This work seeks to provide valuable inputs for developing future research studies on the carbon flux in the lakes of the cold region.

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Study area and samples collection

Major landforms in Northeast China are plains and mountains. In this region, the total area of the lake is approximately 4700 km2, which accounts for 4.6% of the total area of lakes in China. About 60% of lakes greater than 1 km2 are in the Songnen Plain (Song et al., 2018). The Songnen Plain is in the central and western parts of Northeast China, with an area of approximate 23.8 × 104 km2 (Fig. 1). It is a fluvial plain formed by the Songhua and Nenjiang rivers and their tributaries originating from the surrounding mountains. The plain is part of the cold temperate region and has a monsoon climate (Yu et al., 2020). The annual average temperature increases from north to south, from 2 °C to 6 °C. Annually there are only 90–180 frost-free days with a longer icebound season. The coldest month is January when the average temperature ranges between −16 °C and −26 °C. The annual average precipitation ranges from 400 to 500 mm, of which more than 80% of the precipitation occurs in the growing season (from May to October) (Du et al., 2020).
A total of 1026 water samples were collected from 28 lakes and reservoirs (hereafter called lakes) in April, September, and January during the period 2014–2018 for analyzing the plankton biomass and nutrients in the Songnen Plain. The characteristics of these water bodies are shown in Table S1. The latitude of the lakes ranged from 42° N to 50° N (Fig. 1). According to a threshold value of electric conductivity (EC), previously defined (Duarte et al., 2008), these lakes were classified into freshwater bodies (15 lakes, 712 samples) and saline water bodies (13 lakes, 314 samples) with the salinity range of 0.1–4.6 ppts.
In January of each year, the samples were collected when the lakes were completely covered by ice (hereafter called ice-on, n = 727). Samples of ice and water below the ice were collected during the field campaigns using an ice auger in 3–5 sampling points across each lake. The auger was first drilled into the ice for about 30 cm, discarding the surface material, then was drilled into the ice for another 30 cm, and all the ice shavings drilled from that second layer (30–60 cm) were collected and stored in zip lock bags. After, the auger was drilled through the entire ice sheet to collect the underlying waters. Meanwhile, ice thickness was recorded (Song et al., 2019). In April, spring samplings were all conducted when the lakes were completely free of ice. In autumn, the samples were taken in September. In the definition of the term ice-off, in our study, both samples, takenin autumn and spring (n = 299), were included. At each sampling station, water samples (2 L) taken at a depth of 0.5–1 m were placed in a portable refrigerator before they transported to the laboratory.

2.2. Water quality determination

The physicochemical parameters, including EC, pH, salinity, conductivity, and water temperature were determined in situ using a portable multi-parameter analyzer of water quality (YSI 6600, U.S). The thickness of snow and ice in these lakes during winter was also recorded.
In the laboratory, total nitrogen (TN) and total phosphorus (TP) were analyzed by a Continuous Flow Analyzer (SKALAR, San Plus System, Netherlands). TSM was determined gravimetrically (Wen et al., 2019). The water samples were filtered through 0.45 μm mixing fiber Millipore membranes (Bandao Industrial Co., Ltd, China), which were pre-combusted at 450 °C. In this study, DOC was calculated based on the concentrations of dissolved inorganic carbon (DIC) and dissolved total carbon (DTC), both measured using an analyzer of total organic carbon (Shimadzu, TOC- VCPN) (Song et al., 2018). Then these filters were used to determine the concentration of Chla. The filters were extracted using a buffered acetone solution (90%), and the Chla concentration in the extract was determined by spectrophotometry (UV-2600 PC) (Jeffrey and Humphrey, 1975).

2.3. Data analysis

Data analysis was carried as follows: first, the values of nutrients corresponding to all the lakes included in this study were quantified. We used the boxplots and Nonparametric test in SPSS 19.0 software to compare the difference between ice-on and ice-off (spring and autumn) across all waters. Kruskal-Wallis test was used with the sampling season as a fixed factor. Principal component analysis (PCA) in CANOCO 4.5 for Windows software was applied to discern the major variables related to the seasonal differences of these water bodies with centered and standardized variables. Second, a classification regression tree approach (CHAID) was used to examine the relationship between the concentration of Chla and the level of nutrients in winter lakes. The concentration of Chla was taken as the response variable, while the explanatory variables were the concentrations of TN, TP, and DOC in sub-ice water, ice, and in the ice-water difference, before the beginning of the autumn. The mean value and standard error of Chla concentration were calculated for each branch of the regression tree. Spearman's rank correlation analysis was used to characterize the relationship between the concentration of Chla in winter and the explanatory variables, which included the concentration of nutrients, pH, water temperature, TSM, salinity, lake depth, lake area, snow coverage, and the ice thickness. Based on the Spearman's rank correlation coefficients, multiple generalized linear model was applied to determine the relative contribution of each explanatory variable to the spatial variations of the Chla concentration in lakes in winter using the platform of the R software package. Notably, the p-value for each variable was also output, and p < 0.05 indicated a statistically significant contribution.

3. Results and discussion

3.1. Seasonal differences of nutrients and plankton biomass across lakes

The concentration of nutrients corresponding to the samplings carried out in the 28 lakes across the Chinese Songnen Plain was comparatively analyzed in spring, autumn, and winter during 2014–2018 (Fig. 2). According to the Kruskal-Wallis test, a significant difference was observed regarding the concentration of DOC in water samples collected in the lakes (p < 0.01). On the other hand, there was no significant difference for TN or TP in water between ice-on and ice-off (p > 0.05). The concentration of DOC in the lakes ranged from 6.47 to 58.56 mg/L during winter, with a mean value of 22.05 mg/L (Fig. 2a). In spring, a higher concentration of DOC was measured, up to 26.67 mg/L, while in autumn, the lowest values were recorded, up to 12.81 mg/L. The concentrations of TN during these seasons were similar (Fig. 2b). The mean values of TP concentrations in the lakes were also similar during spring (0.51 mg/L) and autumn (0.61 mg/L). It was higher during the ice-on period, with a mean value of 1.01 mg/L (Fig. 2c).
So far, there have been few scientific inputs regarding ecology in winter lakes. The distribution of nutrients and the plankton biomass are both negligible in the north during the frozen period because of the low temperature and unconventional growing season. However, contrary to what is expected, it has been observed a greater abundance of nutrients, phytoplankton, and zooplankton under the ice (Hampton et al., 2017; Jiang et al., 2019). The microbial communities have also been seen to be active (Canelhas et al., 2016; Wand et al., 2006). In this study, the concentrations of nutrients and DOC in lakes were compared to each other and between ice-on and ice-off seasons, during four years. It was found that the concentrations of DOC, TN, and TP were all comparable between the frozen period, spring and autumn. Even so, the concentrations of TP were the highest during the ice-on period. In lake ecosystems, DOC comes from the autochthonous primary production and the allochthonous organic carbon input. In general, the allochthonous DOC represents the main organic carbon source from catchments, which ends in the lakes through rivers and seasonal runoff (Mitrovic and Baldwin, 2016). Due to the spring snowmelt and flushing of soils in the lake watershed, the concentration of DOC always tends to peak during the ice breakup and then recedes rapidly by the winter (Guo et al., 2012). On the other hand, during winter, both the low temperature and snow cover limits the autochthonous primary production and severely hinders the formation of DOC. Furthermore, it is to be noted that the DOC and nutrients concentrations are substantially greater in the underlying waters than those observed in the ice, in the winter lakes (p < 0.05), presumably due to the DOC exclusion during the ice formation (Belzile et al., 2002).
The PCA carried out for all the seasons and considering 10 variables regarding water quality, is shown in Fig. 3a. The first two principal components (PCs) explained 65.5% of the variability in all the selected variables (PC1, 49.0%; PC2, 26.5%). The relatively high loadings on PC1 were TSM and turbidity. The second PCA axis revealed the existence of gradients of nutrients (TN, TP, and DIC). These all had positive loadings on PC2. Furthermore, DOC showed high negative loadings on PC2. A clear difference among different seasons waters was found, as can be seen in Fig. 3b. The samples collected during winter were clustered near each other and were distributed on the positive side of PC2 (except for one point, Fig. 3b), and ice-off samples were also clustered separately.

3.2. Plankton biomass in lakes in winter

Chla, a prominent pigment in phytoplankton and a proxy for phytoplankton biomass, is commonly used as a key indicator of water trophic status (Carlson, 1977; Oliver et al., 2017). Regular monitoring of the level of Chla is important to detect water eutrophication and proactively alert before it becomes a concern (Liu et al., 2020). In this study, there was a remarkable difference in the concentration of Chla observed between ice-on and ice-off seasons (p < 0.01, Table 1). Across all the lakes, average values of Chla (Chla-winter, the sum of Chla concentrations in ice and in sub-ice water) were lower in winter than in spring and autumn (Fig. 4a). This may be related to the light availability since it has been proven that the concentrations of Chla in lakes are positively correlated to the mean light availability (Ma et al., 2016; Phlips et al., 1995). The snow cover alters the light field in ice and underlying waters (Belzile et al., 2002), and the duration of the ice cover may significantly affect the functioning of lakes, especially shallow lakes (Forsstrom et al., 2007). It has been reported that the light in the water column quickly changes from high radiation levels to near darkness when it is snowed (Pelechata et al., 2015), which affects the biological activities in the water column, and ultimately results in a low value of plankton biomass (Song et al., 2019). Compared to other seasons, aquatic organisms are subjected to pressures that hinder survival during the ice-cover periods in lakes. Low water temperature directly affects rates of ecological processes such as photosynthesis, respiration, and growth (Oezkundakci et al., 2016). Besides, unfavorable ecological conditions for plankton are produced when the gas exchange with the atmosphere is hindered, and wind-induced mixing is stopped (Kirillin et al., 2012). This may be another cause that could justify the lowest value of Chla.

In winter, there was a positive correlation between Chla in ice (Chla-ice) and sub-ice water (Chla-water) (R2 = 0.51, Fig. 4b) with a tendency to be greater Chla-water than Chla-ice. This can be explained by the exclusion effects (Song et al., 2019). Moreover, the spatial distribution of Chla-ice and Chla-water may also be related to the ice growth rate and ice structure given by prevailing local weather conditions (Zhang et al., 2012). Ice formation, initiated during a severe and cold winter in Northeast China, can proceed at an accelerated growth rate. As a result, nutrients and Chla of autumn can migrate rapidly to the sub-ice water. The Chla-winter concentratuon different lakes in the same area varied from 1.8 to 81.3 μg/L in this study (Fig. 4a). This Chla-winter difference among different lakes in the same area may be related to the various nutrients in lakes and the snow coverage (Katz et al., 2015). The mean Chla-winter concentratuon in this study was 17.82 μg/L, which was slightly higher than the values in other lakes in different regions. For example, the mean winter Chla concentration in Lake Taihu, a shallow lake in China, was 10.5 μg/L (Deng et al., 2020); the concentrations of Chla under ice varied from 1 to 3 μg/L in Lake Nero, situated in the Upper Volga River Basin (Babanazarova et al., 2013); the total Chla concentrations in surface water collected from Lake Erie in winter ranged from 0.6 to 5.9 μg/L (Twiss et al., 2014).
Regression tree analysis showed that the Chla-winter was influenced by the concentration of TN in the sub-ice water (TNwater). When the TNwater was higher than 2.90 mg/L, the Chla-winter, and the gap between Chla-ice and Chla-water were all significantly increased. The Chla-winter in lakes with the TNwater lower than 2.90 mg/L was also affected by the difference in the concentration of TP between water and the ice (TPcd). When a value of 0.03 mg/L of TPcd was used as a threshold, Chla-winter was approximately 2-fold higher in lakes with a high TPcd (12.88 mg/L) than in lakes with low TPcd (6.33 mg/L) (Fig. 5). The results were consistent with previous studies where it is highlighted the role of nitrogen, needed for protein synthesis, and phosphorus, needed for DNA, RNA, and energy transfer, as the key limiting nutrients for phytoplankton and aquatic plant growth in aquatic ecosystems (Conley et al., 2009; Paerl, 2008). The seasonal ice cover may affect the nitrogen cycle under ice, with important implications for primary productivity (Powers et al., 2017). However, when quantifying the relative importance of TN and TP in the phytoplankton growth in a eutrophic system, the results showed that the reduction in TP should be the priority (Xu et al., 2015). The concentration of Chla in lakes worldwide has increased as a log-linear function by increasing TP concentration (Correll, 1998; Filstrup et al., 2014).
It is worth to note that in this study, the concentration of nutrients during autumn did not show a direct influence on the concentration of Chla-winter. Chla-winter was just directly affected by the nutrients in the ice and sub-ice water during winter. Indirectly, it indicates an absence of symptoms of ecology dysfunction in the sub-ice lake during winter. The growth and reproduction of phytoplankton were limited under ice due to unfavorable environmental conditions, such as low temperature and limited light, although biological processes were not fully affected. It has been shown that nutrients would be expelled from the solid ice matrix and transferred into the aqueous phase during the process of ice formation in the lakes (Belzile et al., 2002; Song et al., 2019). The nutrients in sub-ice water may be concentrated due to the strong exclusion effects of solute during winter, which would provide enough energy and matter for the growth of phytoplankton. However, due to the environmental changes, this could drive the species succession to develop the appropriate functional traits within a given environmental gradient (Oezkundakci et al., 2016; Yang et al., 2016). The phytoplankton community in the sub-ice ecosystem may be different respect to the ice-off periods, and the dominant phytoplankton community may change to other species, what has been observed in some lakes (Dokulil et al., 2016; Kalinowska et al., 2019; Katz et al., 2015). Hence, the examination of changes in the structure of the phytoplankton community, during winter in seasonally ice-covered lakes, may be one effective way to explain the correlations between different seasons.

3.3. Seasonal correlations of plankton biomass in lakes during winter

The levels of Chla showed a strong seasonality as can also be seen in Fig. 4a. The data analysis was conducted to analyze the time series of the Chla concentrations in different lakes between winter and the previous autumn and between winter and the following spring. The results indicate that the Chla-winter concentrations were positively correlated with the previous autumn (rp = 0.563, p < 0.01, Fig. 6a), and there were no correlations with the following spring (rp = 0.061, p > 0.05). The concentrations of DOC and TP in winter lakes were all positively correlated with the concentrations of the previous autumn (Fig. 6b and c).
The seasonal succession in the phytoplankton has been linked to a variety of environmental changes, especially by weather or climatology induced by physicochemical conditions (Yang et al., 2016). Presumably, two pathways would explain the effect of the concentration of Chla during autumn on phytoplankton biomass in winter. The main pathway would be caused as a consequence of derived effects from the level of nutrients from autumn to winter, with a strong carry-over effect on phytoplankton biomass during winter (Figs. 5, 6b and c). The other pathway may be related to the influence of the autumn climate on the phytoplankton community during autumn, which in turn was highly related to the phytoplankton community and biomass in winter. Although the changes in phytoplankton community structure during winter was not analyzed, many studies have found major changes in the taxonomic groups, especially in severe winters, such as an increase in species of the phylum cyanobacteria associated with an increase in the ice thickness and low temperatures, and a dominance of Euglenophyta and Cryptophyta during milder winters (Babanazarova et al., 2013; Lenard and Wojciechowska, 2013; Salonen et al., 2009; Twiss et al., 2014). Based on predictions about phytoplankton succession, it has been seen that overwintering phytoplankton communities are dominated by taxa corresponding to the prevailing conditions in winter lakes, and the phytoplankton biomass may exist and increase during winter (Oezkundakci et al., 2016). Apparently, the first pathway would be more relevant than the second, because the effect due to the phytoplankton succession, in theory, should appear in winter and spring, while there were no correlations of Chla concentration with the following spring (p > 0.05).

3.4. Impact factors for plankton biomass in lakes in winter

The correlation analysis reveals the strongest correlation of Chla concentration in lakes with TPcd, TNwater, TSM, salinity, lake area and depth (p < 0.01), and a weak correlation with DOC, DIC, ice thickness and the snow coverage (p < 0.05) in winter. Based on the correlation analysis results, the effects of above related parameters on Chla-winter, Chla-water, and Chla-ice were analyzed, respectively (Fig. 7). On the whole, the main driving factor of Chla-winter, Chla-ice, and Chla-water in lakes was TPcd (25.5%–35.0%, p < 0.01). Moreover, they were also significantly affected by TNwater (9.2%–11.3%, p < 0.01) and TSM (21.5%–34.0%, p < 0.05). These variables could explain 77.8%, 78.2% and 58.3% of the Chla-winter, Chla-water, and Chla-ice variances, respectively. The relationship could be expressed as follows: Chla-winter = 22.679 × TPcd+8.208 × TNwater+1.721 × TSM-13.143 (R2 = 0.74, p < 0.01).
The effects of the concentrations of TNwater and TPcd on Chla during winter have already been dealt in the previous section. The influence of other impact factors for phytoplankton biomass is addressed in this case. In general, light can be the limiting factor for photosynthesis under the ice in lakes, while ice conditions and overlying snow produces spatial and temporal heterogeneous transmission of light and in addition, alters the spectral distribution. Ice thickness and snow coverage would be the main factors affecting the levels of Chla in lakes, however, their impacts were not significant in this study, denoted by the low contribution to the level of concentration of Chla (0.16%–1.19%, Fig. 7). Contrary, the effects due to the ice duration and its thickness on the phytoplankton community were always observed in the subsequent ice-free seasons (Deng et al., 2020; Gerten and Adrian, 2000; Weyhenmeyer et al., 1999). In addition, the attenuation of light in lakes was mainly affected by phytoplankton, TSM, and yellow substances (Wen et al., 2019). The uniform snow overage and ice thickness in this study resulted in a similar penetration capacity of the sunlight and, a similar photosynthetically active radiation under the ice in lakes. Under those conditions, the light used for photosynthesis in the sub-ice water was mediated by TSM and yellow substances. On the one hand, TSM can influence the photosynthetic process and total primary production in water through absorbing and scattering the sunlight (Du et al., 2020; Wozniak et al., 2018). In turn, TSM included the inorganic particles and pigment particles, which mainly derived from the plankton. With respect to the foregoing, it has been proven that TSM content could increase with Chla in aquatic ecosystems (Marcel et al., 2003; Ylostalo et al., 2014). The water depth of lakes was a key factor regulating the spatial distribution of solutes in the frozen lakes, the lower water depth in the lakes in Songnen Plain could further promote the higher DOC and nutrients concentrations during ice formation (Song et al., 2019), which may be related to the stronger phytoplankton growth and higher Chla concentration in the water. Difference in water depth among the lakes investigated in this study may also be one reason for the various Chla concentration.

4. Conclusions

This study comprehensively investigated the concentrations of Chla in lake ice and underlying waters from 28 lakes across the Songnen Plain, Northeast China. The results showed that, in winter, the phytoplankton survived in sub-ice waters, although the average concentration of Chla was lower in winter than in spring and autumn due to the limited light availability. The main driving factor of the level of Chla in winter was mainly related to the concentration of TN in the sub-ice water and the different concentration level of TP between water and ice, being positively correlated with Chla concentration in the previous autumn (rp = 0.563, p < 0.01). Either in ice or in sub-ice water, Chla concentrations were also significantly affected by TSM (p < 0.05). TNwater, TPcd, and TSM could totally explain 77.8% of the variances in the concentration of Chla during winter. There is growing interest in winter ecosystems in terms of phytoplankton to help understand the potentially important implications for annual lake biogeochemical loads and primary productivity. The present study, carried out in the cold region, may serve as a framework for future research or global scaling studies concerning seasonally ice-covered lakes.

  • Analysis of the distribution across media, migration, and related driving factors of fluoride in cold and arid lakes during the freezing period

    2024, Environmental Research
    Citation Excerpt :

    Surface water of the lake freezes in November, with the ice layer persisting for 5–6 months. Lake freezing concentrates pollutants into the water body under the ice, thereby further aggravating water pollution (Yang et al., 2019; Zhou et al., 2020; Chu et al., 2017; Wen et al., 2020). The present study aimed to characterize the occurrence and dispersion of F− across lake ice, water, and sediment in cold and arid regions, its migration and transformation during the freezing period, and driving factors, focusing on Lake Ulansuhai as being a typical cold and arid/semi-arid region lake.

  • Spatiotemporal variability and environmental effects of greenhouse gases, nutrients, and dissolved carbons in an ice-covered reservoir

    2023, Environmental Research
    Citation Excerpt :

    The environmental impacts of ice-covered reservoirs are more abrupt and prompt than those of non-ice-covered reservoirs in terms of water quality and GHGs (as discussed in Section 4.1). Phytoplankton are mostly dormant due to cold temperatures in the water column during winter (Wen et al., 2020) and the warmer temperatures in spring lead to increased phytoplankton activity, coupled with catchment nutrient input and winter nutrient accumulation. The combination of these favorable conditions results in faster emergence and a greater risk of eutrophication in spring.

    2023, Environmental Research

(2005) studied the relationship between Chl-a and several biotic and abiotic water quality variables by using the principal component score in multiple linear regression analysis (MLR) to predict Chl-a levels in a reservoir. Wen et al. (2020) quantified the main factors affecting the level of Chl-a under the ice in the lakes in Northeast China utilizing the classification regression tree approach (CHAID). However, these methods only explored the relationship between Chl-a concentrations and correlated factors.
